english:
  title: Record of the Dongnae Fortress
  author: Lee Chaem
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Our realm has long been celebrated for its skill in defending cities, even in the age of divided kingdoms. In those three ancient states, Eulji Mundeok held the isolated city of Pyongyang against the armies of the world—surely he possessed the secrets of fortification, methods by which the weak could master the strong. Yet after unification brought peace to all directions, walls were torn down to make fields, moats filled to build homes, weapons melted for fuel. In such tranquility, those who knew the art of defense aged and died, and their knowledge perished with them.

    When hardship returned to our nation's fortune and Khitan warriors breached our walls in sudden assault, we scrambled without strategy. Though we hastily repaired what was broken, we had lost the true way of defense. Won Chung-gap held Tiger Peak fortress and drove back the invaders through personal valor and righteousness—yet this was the triumph of one man's courage, not the restoration of ancient wisdom.

    Since the Year of the Dog, Japanese pirates have ravaged our borders with increasing fury. The throne grew anxious, ministers offered counsel, but their strategy was flawed: rather than strengthen our walls, they counseled clearing the fields and waiting for the enemy to withdraw of their own accord. This folly only drew the invaders deeper while leaving our soldiers without shelter.

    Now our Commander Park, when once he served as magistrate of Gimhae, rebuilt망산 Fortress and perfected both its defenses and the methods to hold them. When raiders came swarming like ants, the commander ordered his men to the walls. Arrows and stones rained down. The enemy scattered, bleeding and fleeing, unable to breach that solitary, defiant citadel. When he presented the severed heads to court, the King spoke to his ministers: "A fortress, though small, can master a mighty force; the few can stand against the many; those at rest can overcome the weary." He then commanded every coastal prefecture to build such fortifications, and from that day forward, the border remained at peace until this present time.

    When the Commander came to the ruins of Dongnae, he saw only desolation—fields overgrown, homesteads abandoned. His heart was moved to restore it. He gathered the officers and magistrates and spoke: "Dongnae stands foremost among the southeastern towns. Its seas teem with abundance, its soil yields prosperity—the treasury depends upon it. To the east lies Haewun Terrace, where immortals once came to play. To the north flows the hot spring where ancient kings bathed. Eight or nine places are named for such celestial beauty, yet all lie in ruin. As a commander, can I shirk this duty? Let us rebuild these walls, gather the people, restore the settlement, and replenish the realm's coffers."

    He assured them: "If we fortify this place, it shall stand like a tripod between Gimhae and Ulsan, with patrol boats stationed below our walls. The enemy will have nothing to fear from us."

    All agreed without hesitation. The Commander issued his orders on the nineteenth day of the eighth month in the Year of the Rabbit. Within a month, the work was complete. He asked me to record this achievement.

    I said: "Commander, your fortress will serve the entire nation. The official histories will surely follow the example of the Spring and Autumn Annals, which recorded the building of cities at Xing and Chu Qiu. What presumption it would be for me to add my clumsy words to such chronicles."

    Yet I could not refuse entirely. For this I know: people endure through walls, and walls endure through virtue. Thus the appointment of worthy men is the rarest of achievements. The Book of Poetry records how the Duke of Shao built walls at Xie and Zhongshan Fu fortified Qi—both possessed men of true capability. What shall the Commander choose to embody?
  footnotes:
    - 'Eulji Mundeok (을지문덕): A legendary Goguryeo general credited with defeating Chinese forces during the Sui Dynasty invasion.'
    - 'Year of the Dog (경인년): Refers to 1350, during the reign of King Chungjeong of Goryeo.'
    - 'Gimhae and Ulsan: Strategic locations forming a triangle of defense with Dongnae.'
    - 'Year of the Rabbit (정묘년): 1351.'
    - 'Duke of Shao and Zhongshan Fu: Historical figures from ancient China known for righteous governance and wise administration, referenced from the Book of Poetry.'
